  "prompt": "\"CAS PRES CHQ\" what does this SBI statement message mean?",
  "response": "The statement message **\"CAS PRES CHQ\"** on your SBI (State Bank of India) account typically stands for **\"Cash Presentation Cheque.\"** Here's a breakdown of the abbreviation:\n\n- **CAS**: **Cash**\n- **PRES**: **Presentation**\n- **CHQ**: **Cheque**\n\n### What It Means:\n\n1. **Cheque Presentation for Cash Withdrawal:**\n   - If you **issued a cheque** and it's been presented by the payee for cash, the amount will be **debited** from your account. This means you've withdrawn cash against the cheque you provided.\n\n2. **Cheque Deposit Processed:**\n   - If you **deposited a cheque**, \"CAS PRES CHQ\" might indicate that the cheque has been presented by SBI for clearing and the amount will be **credited** to your account once the cheque is successfully processed.\n\n### Actions to Take:\n\n- **Verify Transaction Details:**\n  - Check the **transaction amount** alongside \"CAS PRES CHQ\" in your statement to determine whether it was a debit (cash withdrawal) or a credit (cheque deposit).\n  \n- **Review Account Activity:**\n  - Look at surrounding transactions for additional context that might clarify the nature of this entry.\n\n- **Contact SBI Customer Support:**\n  - If you're unsure about this transaction or if something doesn't seem right, it's best to **reach out directly to SBI** through their customer service channels for a precise explanation.\n\n### Example Scenarios:\n\n- **Debit Scenario:**\n  - You wrote a cheque to a vendor, and upon presentation, SBI debited your account. The statement would show \"CAS PRES CHQ\" as a debit entry.\n\n- **Credit Scenario:**\n  - You deposited a cheque, and once it's processed, SBI credits your account. The statement would show \"CAS PRES CHQ\" as a credit entry.\n\nUnderstanding these abbreviations can help you better track and manage your bank transactions. Always ensure to keep an eye on your account statements for any unfamiliar entries and consult your bank if you have questions.",
